<h2>Queries</h2>

<p>On the <a href="query">query</a> page, give MScanner examples of the
citations you are looking for, then click "Submit Query". About 90 seconds from
the front of the queue the result will be ready. The difference between
MScanner and the PubMed <a
href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query/static/computation.html">Related
Articles</a> feature is that MScanner can use many examples to define the topic
of interest, instead of just one.</p>

<p>See the <a href="static/sample/pg07">sample output</a> of a query that used
as input 1,595 citations from the Pharmacogenetics KnowledgeBase (<a
href="http://www.pharmgkb.org">PharmGKB</a>).</p>

<h2>Cross validation</h2> 

<p>If MScanner is given random articles for input, those citations are
indistinguishable from the rest of <a
href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/pubs/factsheets/medline.html">Medline</a>. To
measure how well MScanner can distinguish your input from Medline, use the
10-fold cross validation option on the query page (which requires 30 or more
training citations). See the <a href="static/sample/pg07-vs-100k">sample
output</a> for cross validation using the PharmGKB citations as input.</p>

